Host-side API proxy — the offline cage's sole egress path. It listens on a UNIX socket bind-mounted into the cage at `/run/ctx/api.sock` (the in-cage relay forwards `127.0.0.1:8080` there); per connection it reads the HTTP/1.1 request head, rewrites it, dials upstream over TLS, and pumps bytes both directions.

Two auth postures determined by `ProxyConfig.api_key`: `Some(key)` strips any client-supplied `x-api-key`/`Authorization` header and injects the real key host-side (the cage never sees the real credential); `None` passes the client's `Authorization` through untouched (subscription-OAuth posture, where the bound credential itself authenticates and the proxy's only job is being the sole controlled egress). This branching lives in `is_owned_header`/`rewrite_head`.

TLS and process/socket plumbing are quarantined behind the `Upstream` trait (`connect(&self) -> Result<UpstreamIo, CageError>`) specifically so no TLS stack has to enter this crate — the real implementation, `SocatUpstream`, shells out to `socat - OPENSSL:<host>:443,verify=1,cafile=...` with a long `-t 86400` half-close timeout, called out in a comment as "the ADR-028 lesson" (i.e. a prior bug where premature socket closure truncated responses). Tests/other callers can substitute a fake `Upstream`.

`rewrite_head(head: &str, cfg: &ProxyConfig) -> String` is a pure function (no I/O) over the request head text, easy to unit-test in isolation: it drops any `Host:`/`Connection:` header (and `x-api-key:`/`Authorization:` when `api_key.is_some()`), then appends proxy-controlled `Host`, optional `x-api-key`, and always `Connection: close` — every request gets its own upstream connection, so keep-alive is intentionally never used. `head` is expected to exclude the trailing blank line.

`read_head` enforces `MAX_HEAD = 64 * 1024` and returns `CageError::Protocol` on EOF-before-terminator or oversized head — this is the request-smuggling/DoS guard, not deducible from the type signature alone. `serve_conn` propagates errors from head-read/dial/initial-write but treats pump-phase failures as a silent connection close (best-effort, not error-propagated) — `pump` swallows all read/write errors by design. `serve` runs a nonblocking accept loop polled every `ACCEPT_IDLE` (20ms), spawning one thread per connection and checking `stop: &AtomicBool` each iteration for cooperative shutdown; connection failures are logged to stderr but don't stop the loop.

No async runtime — everything is blocking I/O plus raw `std::thread` spawns, one thread per connection plus one extra thread per connection for the reverse-direction pump in `serve_conn`.